name: XVerExtensionCitation.citedArtifact
title: Cross-Version Extension for FHIR R5:Citation.citedArtifact compared to FHIR R4
description: Citation.citedArtifact does not exist in target and has no mapping

element.short: The article or artifact being described
element.definition: Citation.citedArtifact does not exist in target and has no mapping

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children
Must have either extensions or value[x], not both

element.short: Unique id for inter-element referencing
element.definition: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

slicing.description: Extensions are always sliced by (at least) url

element.short: Additional content defined by implementations
element.definition: May be used to represent additional information that is not part of the basic definition of the element. To make the use of extensions safe and managable, there is a strict set of governance applied to the definition and use of extensions. Though any implementer can define an extension, there is a set of requirements that SHALL be met as part of the definition of the extension.
element.comment: There can be no stigma associated with the use of extensions by any application, project, or standard - regardless of the institution or jurisdiction that uses or defines the extensions.  The use of extensions is what allows the FHIR specification to retain a core level of simplicity for everyone.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children
Must have either extensions or value[x], not both

element.short: identifies the meaning of the extension
element.definition: Source of the definition for the extension code - a logical name or a URL.
element.comment: The definition may point directly to a computable or human-readable definition of the extensibility codes, or it may be a logical URI as declared in some other specification. The definition SHALL be a URI for the Structure Definition defining the extension.

element.short: Value of extension
element.definition: Value of extension - must be one of a constrained set of the data types (see [Extensibility](extensibility.html) for a list).

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: Unique identifier. May include DOI, PMID, PMCID, etc
element.definition: A formal identifier that is used to identify the cited artifact when it is represented in other formats, or referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance.
element.comment: This element will contain unique identifiers that support de-duplication of citations. Commonly used identifiers for study citations include digital object identifier (DOI), PubMed ID (PMID), and PubMed Central ID (PMCID). To maintain interoperability, the suggested identifier.system values to use for these 3 identifiers are: DOI = "https://doi.org" PMID = "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov" PMCID = "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/"

element.short: Identifier not unique to the cited artifact. May include trial registry identifiers
element.definition: A formal identifier that is used to identify things closely related to the cited artifact.
element.comment: May include trial registry identifiers, e.g. NCT04372602 from clinicaltrials.gov. This related identifier would not be used as unique identifier for the cited artifact itself. Multiple published articles (each with their own unique identifier) may relate to the same study record in a research registry. Commonly used related identifiers for study registries include ClinicalTrials.gov identifier (NCTId) and PROSPERO identifier (used for registration of systematic reviews). To maintain interoperability, the suggested identifier.system values to use for these 2 identifiers are: ClinicalTrials.gov = "https://clinicaltrials.gov" PROSPERO = "https://www.crd.york.ac.uk/prospero/"

element.short: When the cited artifact was accessed
element.definition: Use this element when citing an artifact from a potentially unstable source, such as a webpage, to note the date (and time) the source was accessed.

element.short: The defined version of the cited artifact
The version number or other version identifier
Citation for the main version of the cited artifact
element.definition: When referencing a baseCitation, one may inherit any data from the referenced Citation Resource and consider any data in the current Citation Resource as superceding to be version-specific.

element.short: The status of the cited artifact
An effective date or period for a status of the cited artifact
element.definition: An effective date or period, historical or future, actual or expected, for a status of the cited artifact.

element.short: Classification of the status
element.definition: A definition of the status associated with a date or period.

element.short: Either occurred or expected
When the status started and/or ended
element.definition: For an instance, place the same value in both start and end elements.

element.short: The title details of the article or artifact
The kind of title
element.definition: Used to express the reason for or classification of the title.

element.short: Used to express the specific language
element.definition: Used to express the specific language of the title.

element.short: The title of the article or artifact
Summary of the article or artifact
element.definition: The abstract may be used to convey article-contained abstracts, externally-created abstracts, or other descriptive summaries.

element.short: The kind of abstract
element.definition: Used to express the reason for or classification of the abstract.

element.short: Used to express the specific language
element.definition: Used to express the specific language of the abstract.

element.short: Abstract content
Copyright notice for the abstract
element.definition: There is also a copyright element in the publicationForm element, so this copyright element is intended for copyright of the abstract.

element.short: The component of the article or artifact
The kind of component
The specification of the component
The citation for the full article or artifact
element.definition: When referencing a baseCitation, one may inherit any data from the referenced Citation Resource and consider any data in the current Citation Resource as superceding to be specific to the citation of the specified part. For example, the part-specific Citation may have additional contributorship data that supercedes the contributorship data for the full citation when there is a need to uniquely report the contributorship for an image or supplement associated with the fuller citation record.

element.short: The artifact related to the cited artifact
element.definition: The citedArtifact.relatesTo element uses a BackboneElement instead of the RelatedArtifact Datatype to enable use of an extended value set for the required code for the type of relationship.

element.short: documentation | justification | citation | predecessor | successor | derived-from | depends-on | composed-of | part-of | amends | amended-with | appends | appended-with | cites | cited-by | comments-on | comment-in | contains | contained-in | corrects | correction-in | replaces | replaced-with | retracts | retracted-by | signs | similar-to | supports | supported-with | transforms | transformed-into | transformed-with | documents | specification-of | created-with | cite-as | reprint | reprint-of
element.definition: The type of relationship to the related artifact.

element.short: Additional classifiers
element.definition: Provides additional classifiers of the related artifact.

element.short: Short label
element.definition: A short label that can be used to reference the related artifact from elsewhere in the containing artifact, such as a footnote index.
element.comment: Though not commonly used in citation records, this could be used for referencing other articles in the abstract or explanatory notes.

element.short: Brief description of the related artifact
element.definition: A brief description of the document or knowledge resource being referenced, suitable for display to a consumer.

element.short: Bibliographic citation for the artifact
element.definition: A bibliographic citation for the related artifact. This text SHOULD be formatted according to an accepted citation format.

element.short: What document is being referenced
element.definition: The document being referenced, represented as an attachment. Do not use this element if using the resource element to provide the canonical to the related artifact.
element.comment: To refer to related artifacts by URL, the FHIR Attachment Datatype includes a url element, so the path would be Citation.citedArtifact.relatesTo.document.url

element.short: What artifact is being referenced
element.definition: The related artifact, such as a library, value set, profile, or other knowledge resource.
element.comment: If the type is predecessor, this is a reference to the succeeding knowledge resource. If the type is successor, this is a reference to the prior knowledge resource

element.short: What artifact, if not a conformance resource
element.definition: The related artifact, if the artifact is not a canonical resource, or a resource reference to a canonical resource.
element.comment: If both resource and resourceReference are present, they SHOULD be consistent and reference the same resource. Although relatedArtifact is intended to support references to definitional resources, there are cases where non-definitional resources can be definitional (such as Location where the kind is mode). Related artifacts SHOULD be used to reference definitional resources, and profiles SHOULD be used to make that explicit for particular use cases.

element.short: If multiple, used to represent alternative forms of the article that are not separate citations
element.definition: A common use is a journal article with a publication date and pagination for a print version and a different publication date for the online version of the same article.

element.short: The collection the cited article or artifact is published in
Kind of container (e.g. Periodical, database, or book)
element.definition: Journals and newspapers are coded as Periodical.

element.short: Journal identifiers include ISSN, ISO Abbreviation and NLMuniqueID; Book identifiers include ISBN
Name of the database or title of the book or journal
element.definition: ClinicalTrials.gov is a name of a database.

element.short: Name of or resource describing the publisher
Geographic location of the publisher
Internet or Print
element.definition: Describes the form of the medium cited. Common codes are "Internet" or "Print". The CitedMedium value set has 6 codes. The codes internet, print, and offline-digital-storage are the common codes for a typical publication form, though internet and print are more common for study citations. Three additional codes (each appending one of the primary codes with "-without-issue" are used for situations when a study is published both within an issue (of a periodical release as commonly done for journals) AND is published separately from the issue (as commonly done with early online publication), to represent specific identification of the publication form not associated with the issue.

element.short: Volume number of journal or other collection in which the article is published
Issue, part or supplement of journal or other collection in which the article is published
The date the article was added to the database, or the date the article was released
element.definition: The articleDate is the preferred element for expressing the publication date as structured data.

element.short: Text representation of the date on which the issue of the cited artifact was published
element.definition: The publicationDateText element is prefererntially used when a date is not represented in a form that can be handled as structured data in other elements.

element.short: Season in which the cited artifact was published
element.definition: Spring, Summer, Fall/Autumn, Winter.

element.short: The date the article was last revised or updated in the database
element.definition: The lastRevisionDate is used for the cited article and not the date the Citation Resource is last revised.

element.short: Language(s) in which this form of the article is published
element.definition: The language or languages in which this form of the article is published.

element.short: Entry number or identifier for inclusion in a database
element.definition: Accession numbers may be used instead of or in addition to page numbers.  Accession numbers are functionally identifiers when coupled with the identity of the database for which they are accession numbers. Accession numbers which are used for indexing citations in a dataset of citations should NOT be entered in Citation.citedArtifact.publicationForm.accessionNumber -- this use would be a type of Citation.identifier for the citation record itself.

element.short: Used for full display of pagination
Used for isolated representation of first page
Used for isolated representation of last page
Number of pages or screens
element.definition: Actual or approximate number of pages or screens. Distinct from reporting the page numbers.

element.short: Copyright notice for the full article or artifact
element.definition: It is possible that different publication forms have different copyright notices.

element.short: Used for any URL for the article or artifact cited
Code the reason for different URLs, e.g. abstract and full-text
element.definition: A characterization of the object expected at the web location.
element.comment: Categories that may be frequently used for study citations may include abstract, full-text, supplement, webpage, and doi-based.

element.short: The specific URL
element.definition: Persistent URLs, like doi, are preferred.

element.short: The assignment to an organizing scheme
The kind of classifier (e.g. publication type, keyword)
The specific classification value
Complex or externally created classification
element.definition: Examples relevant to study citations include MeSH Headings or Keywords that contain qualifier codings or sub-classifications, and include risk of bias assessments created by persons different from the creator of the citation record.

element.short: Attribution of authors and other contributors
element.definition: This element is used to list authors and other contributors, their contact information, specific contributions, and summary statements.

element.short: Indicates if the list includes all authors and/or contributors
element.definition: If list is incomplete, "et al" can be appended to Contributorship.summary.value for display purposes.

element.short: An individual entity named as a contributor
element.definition: An individual entity named as a contributor, for example in the author list or contributor list.
element.comment: Used to report contributorship in individualized ways.

element.short: The identity of the individual contributor
element.definition: If naming a contributor without additional detail or further structured data, the display element within the Reference datatype may be used for a simple string without referencing another resource.

element.short: For citation styles that use initials
element.definition: This element is used to support a data element used for citations that is not otherwise supported fully by FHIR HumanName datatype. In some citation summary styles (e.g. Medline), authors are presented with full spelling of their last name (family name) and initials for all forenames (first names, middle names, preceding names, given names). As the FHIR HumanName Datatype does not have a specific element for forename initials and this is common in citation usage, the element is added to contributorship.entry directly.

element.short: Organizational affiliation
element.definition: Organization affiliated with the contributor.
element.comment: If naming an organization without additional detail or further structured data, the display element within the Reference datatype may be used for a simple string without referencing another resource.

element.short: The specific contribution
element.definition: This element identifies the specific nature of an individualâ€™s contribution with respect to the cited work.
element.comment: The CreDiT taxonomy provides a way to encode contribution information. The purpose of CRediT is to provide transparency in contributions to scholarly published work, to enable improved systems of attribution, credit, and accountability.

element.short: The role of the contributor (e.g. author, editor, reviewer, funder)
Contributions with accounting for time or number
The specific contribution
The time that the contribution was made
Whether the contributor is the corresponding contributor for the role
element.definition: If there are multiple authors and one serves as the corresponding author, then that one would have correspondingContact = true.

element.short: Ranked order of contribution
element.definition: Provides a numerical ranking to represent the degree of contributorship relative to other contributors, such as 1 for first author and 2 for second author.
element.comment: Used to retain order of authorship as structured data

element.short: Used to record a display of the author/contributor list without separate data element for each list member
Such as author list, contributorship statement, funding statement, acknowledgements statement, or conflicts of interest statement
element.definition: Used most commonly to express an author list or a contributorship statement.

element.short: The format for the display string
element.definition: The format for the display string, such as author last name with first letter capitalized followed by forename initials.

element.short: Used to code the producer or rule for creating the display string
The display string for the author list, contributor list, or contributorship statement

element.definition: Spring, Summer, Fall/Autumn, Winter.

element.short: The date the article was last revised or updated in the database
element.definition: The lastRevisionDate is used for the cited article and not the date the Citation Resource is last revised.

element.short: Language(s) in which this form of the article is published
element.definition: The language or languages in which this form of the article is published.

element.short: Entry number or identifier for inclusion in a database
element.definition: Accession numbers may be used instead of or in addition to page numbers.  Accession numbers are functionally identifiers when coupled with the identity of the database for which they are accession numbers. Accession numbers which are used for indexing citations in a dataset of citations should NOT be entered in Citation.citedArtifact.publicationForm.accessionNumber -- this use would be a type of Citation.identifier for the citation record itself.

element.definition: Actual or approximate number of pages or screens. Distinct from reporting the page numbers.

element.short: Copyright notice for the full article or artifact
element.definition: It is possible that different publication forms have different copyright notices.

element.comment: Categories that may be frequently used for study citations may include abstract, full-text, supplement, webpage, and doi-based.

element.short: Attribution of authors and other contributors
element.definition: This element is used to list authors and other contributors, their contact information, specific contributions, and summary statements.

element.short: Indicates if the list includes all authors and/or contributors
element.definition: If list is incomplete, "et al" can be appended to Contributorship.summary.value for display purposes.

element.short: An individual entity named as a contributor
element.definition: An individual entity named as a contributor, for example in the author list or contributor list.
element.comment: Used to report contributorship in individualized ways.

element.short: The identity of the individual contributor
element.definition: If naming a contributor without additional detail or further structured data, the display element within the Reference datatype may be used for a simple string without referencing another resource.

element.short: For citation styles that use initials
element.definition: This element is used to support a data element used for citations that is not otherwise supported fully by FHIR HumanName datatype. In some citation summary styles (e.g. Medline), authors are presented with full spelling of their last name (family name) and initials for all forenames (first names, middle names, preceding names, given names). As the FHIR HumanName Datatype does not have a specific element for forename initials and this is common in citation usage, the element is added to contributorship.entry directly.

element.short: Organizational affiliation
element.definition: Organization affiliated with the contributor.
element.comment: If naming an organization without additional detail or further structured data, the display element within the Reference datatype may be used for a simple string without referencing another resource.

element.comment: The CreDiT taxonomy provides a way to encode contribution information. The purpose of CRediT is to provide transparency in contributions to scholarly published work, to enable improved systems of attribution, credit, and accountability.
